### What to Do

Implement collapsible/expandable sections in tree output for packs with many patterns. This is a FUTURE enhancement that depends on rich_rust capabilities.

### Problem

A pack with 50+ patterns creates overwhelming output:
```
kubernetes_base
├── pattern_1
├── pattern_2
... 48 more lines ...
└── pattern_50
```

### Target UX

```
kubernetes_base (50 patterns)
├── kubectl_delete_ns
├── kubectl_delete_pvc
├── [dim]... 45 more patterns (use --expand to show all)[/]
├── helm_uninstall
└── kubectl_drain
```

### Implementation Options

#### Option A: Static truncation (simpler)
```rust
fn render_pack_patterns(pack: &Pack, max_show: usize) -> TreeNode {
    let patterns = &pack.patterns;
    let total = patterns.len();

    let mut node = TreeNode::new(format!(
        "[cyan]{}[/] ({} patterns)",
        pack.name, total
    ));

    if total <= max_show {
        for p in patterns {
            node.add(p.id.as_str());
        }
    } else {
        // Show first few
        for p in patterns.iter().take(3) {
            node.add(p.id.as_str());
        }
        // Truncation message
        node.add(format!(
            "[dim]... {} more patterns (--expand to show all)[/]",
            total - 6
        ));
        // Show last few
        for p in patterns.iter().rev().take(3).rev() {
            node.add(p.id.as_str());
        }
    }

    node
}
```

#### Option B: Interactive (requires rich_rust Live support)

This would require terminal interactivity that may not be suitable for dcg's use case. Mark as future/optional.

### CLI Flags

Add `--expand` or `--max-patterns <N>` to `dcg packs --tree`:
```rust
#[derive(Parser)]
struct PacksCommand {
    #[arg(long)]
    tree: bool,

    #[arg(long, default_value = "10")]
    max_patterns: usize,

    #[arg(long)]
    expand: bool,  // Show all patterns
}
```

### Considerations

- Default to showing ~10 patterns max
- Always show first and last few (context)
- Clear indication of truncation
- Works without interactivity (dcg is non-interactive)
